    <center><table class="itemDisplayTable">
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Title:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Role of Leadership on Women Empowerment among the SHG’s - A Study with Special Reference to Kancheepuram District, Tamilnadu</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Authors:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Chitra.S</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Keywords:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Women Empowerment<br />Kancheepuram District</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Issue Date:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Sep-2013 </td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Publisher:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">SRM University</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Series/Report no.:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">T0126</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Abstract:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Self-Help Group or in-short SHG is now a well-known concept which is now
almost two decade old. It is reported that the SHGs have a role in hastening country’s
economic development. SHGs have now evolved as a movement. Mainly, members
of the SHGs are women. Consequently, participation of women in the country’s
economic development is increasing. They also play an important role in elevating
the economic status of their families. This has led boost to the process of women’s
empowerment. The origin of SHGs is from the brainchild of Grameen Bank of
Bangladesh, which was founded by Mohammed Yunus. SHGs were started and
formed in 1975. In India NABARD is initiated in 1986-87. But the real effort was
taken after 1991-92 from the linkage of SHGs with the banks. A SHG is a small
economically homogeneous affinity group of the rural poor voluntarily coming
together to save small amount regularly, which are deposited in a common fund to
meet members emergency needs and to provide collateral free loans decided by the
group. (Abhaskumar Jha 2000).
Running a Self Help Group is not as easy as it seems. There must be sincere
willingness to learn and then practice what is taught to make a difference. Effective
support leaders and facilitators: Leader should be knowledgeable of group behaviors.
Leaders/facilitators tend to have familiarity with or past experience as group leaders.
It is very useful to understand how people behave in groups and how helpful they can
be to one another in a group setting and possess a basic commitment to the self-help
process. Leading an effective self-help group begins with a commitment to three
basic assumptions: each member can make a contribution, each member is the
ultimate authority on their needs and what will work for them, and communication
must be open and honest to promote a positive group experience.
Off late it was identified that the women SHGs are not performing up to the
expectations due to lack of awareness on the role of a member and leadership related
issues. In this regard the banks started penalizing by reducing the loan amounts and
the governmental agencies are decoupled from the responsibility of guaranteeing to
banks. In this scenario many SHGs are closed and some of them are restructured by
merging with other groups. Many research studies are focused on assessing the
performance and models and the modus operandi, nature of business and success of
SHGs in the country.
The present study is conducted with a primary objective to analyze the role of
leadership in empowerment of women in Self Help Groups and to estimate the
dimension of empowerment is influenced by leadership among women in self help
groups.
The study is mainly based on primary data which is collected from the 300
SHG members and leaders located in different villages in Kancheepuram district.
This is ensured to get the exact number of sample size determined as per scientific
method. The SHGs are chosen according to the convenience of the researcher. The
sample villages are selected in random and respondents are chosen conveniently from
the selected SHGs in Kancheepuram district. The data required for the study is
collected from both primary and secondary sources. The primary data is collected
through a structured questionnaire. The secondary data is collected from various print
and electronic media sources. The data related to previous research is obtained from
the university libraries of the reputed universities in the Chennai city.
Initially a pilot study was conducted with 80 samples. The relevance of some
questions was slightly modified for final version of questionnaire. The reliability
coefficient of the questionnaire is computed using Corn Bach’s Alpha and the value
is 0.91, which shows that the instrument is reliable. At this point a questionnaire in
Tamil (Vernacular Language) has also been prepared to cover and collect the
opinions of all in the survey. The questionnaire is distributed to all and asked to fill
by understanding one by one.
The analysis of the present study is made in two parts. Part-I deals with the
analyzing of the Micro finance climate and SHGs existence and the related aspects
and climate using descriptive statistics. Part II deals with the studying of the
relationship between the demographical traits and the selected variables influencing
women empowerment in the sample area., namely, leadership styles observed;
reasons for adopting a particular leadership style, factors influencing women
empowerment in the SHGs, role of leadership in the success of SHGs and women
empowerment etc.
The study reveals that, cent percent of the women in self help groups agreed
that the role of a leader is indispensable and a leadership has lot of impact on
planning, directing, coordinating, communicating and controlling the activities of a
group from time to time. A committed leader can always take suggestions from the
members and also co-operates, in the process of learning.
The detailed dimensions of empowerment achieved by the below 20 years
young women among self help groups are Improved personal confidence level with
the mean value of 4.34, Identification of potential skills with the mean value of 3.74,
Improved organization and Leadership skills with the mean value of 3.74, Improved
communication and co-ordination skills with the mean value of 3.60, Improved
socializing skills with the mean value of 3.88, Improved level of financial awareness
and literacy with the mean value of 3.59, Improved market awareness and marketing
tricks with the mean value of 3.61, Self realization of value of education and
priorities in life with the mean value of 3.52, Realizing the value of money and
savings with the mean value of 3.75, Capacity to plan better and complete the task
with the mean value of 3.45, Improved level of prioritizing the things at home with
the mean value of 3.68, Improved level of public speaking and public relations with
the mean value of 3.41, Awareness on personal grooming and cleanliness with the
mean value of 3.41, Improved level of awareness on health and hygiene with the
mean value of 3.83, Awareness on Socio economic scenario of markets with the
mean value of 3.60 respectively.
The different degrees of role played by leadership in the empowerment of
women in self help groups are as follows. Leader can create the awareness among
peers with the mean score of 4.39; Leader can show a role model attitude with the
mean score of 3.85; Leader can bring a change in thinking patterns with the mean
score of 3.67; Leader can motivate members to learn with the mean score of 3.60;
Leadership style plays a role in profit sharing patterns with the mean value of 3.61;
Leadership brings awareness on the rights and duties of members 3.60; and
Leadership brings awareness on women protection and gender discrimination 3.77
respectively. This clearly indicates that Leadership plays a greater role in women
empowerment in terms of creating awareness, setting model behavior, change agent,
awareness on rights and duties, protection and gender discrimination. This indicates
the indispensible role of a leader in the women empowerment.
The role of leadership plays a vital role in the empowerment of women in self
help groups in the sample area. This indicates the need and importance of leadership
and its effectiveness to lead and effectively operationalise the schemes introduced by
the government to empower the women in rural areas and the society at large. A
successful leader is one who creates a spark and enlightens the followers by guiding
and advising for the benefit of the members and to the society at large. Such
initiatives adopted and followed by the leaders in the sample area to empower the
women in socio economic dimensions are empirically proved in this study</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">URI:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/13832">http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/13832</a></td></tr>
